    value: 曰
english:
  title: 'Twin-Rhyme Lotus Palindrome: A Poem on Solitary Dwelling'
  author: Park Yeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The ancients composed palindromic verses in various forms—the Ten-Character style, the Xuanji style, the Jade Linked-Ring style, the Brocade-Twined-Branch style—each with its own distinct structure. Today, I do not merely follow the old paths but create anew two five-character quatrains, rendered as a lotus flower in form, sent to offer meaning to the noble heart. I name it the Lotus Palindrome.

    Alone I dwell, content in leisure,
    My body at rest in this small garden.
    The valley's closeness suits this humble dwelling,
    The creek runs fine, near the clear wine vessel.
    Bamboo stands verdant where moonlight lingers,
    Mountains wear green crowned with white clouds.
    My heart yearns keenly to learn of immortals,
    Yet difficult it is when the world churns in turmoil.

    Solitary in this shadowed retreat, joy deepens,
    I keep my place, guarding forest and hill.
    The valley's depth conceals the weathered dwelling,
    Its waters clear, mirrored in the resting vessel.
    Bamboo sparse, it sieves the pale moonbeams,
    Distant mountains release the idle clouds.
    Eager to study the Way through constant refinement—
    Yet how hard to untangle the world's confusion.
  footnotes:
    - This work represents an innovative approach to palindromic poetry (회문시), a traditional form that reads the same forwards and backwards. Park Yeon's composition employs a lotus flower structure, where the poetic form itself mirrors the symmetry of nature.
    - The twin quatrains present complementary meditations on hermitic life—the first celebrating the desire for transcendence amid worldly turbulence, the second reflecting on the disciplined practice required to understand the Dao. The parallels and variations between them create a deliberate poetic echo.
